This page explains the values associated with the tag for {{Tagname|event structure}} -- see also the [[Tagset|tagset]].
The values associated with event structure are {{Tagname|repeated}}, {{Tagname|stative}}, {{Tagname|ongoing}}, and {{Tagname|bounded}}. All descriptions of events that involve multiple instances of the same action are to be tagged as repeated. The distinctions into bounded, ongoing, and stative only apply to descriptions of individual events or actions.
===Stative=== If an event is described as stative, its description implies little if any internal event dynamics. Such descriptions typically involve stative predicates such as ''be asleep'', ''be alive'', ''be cold'' etc.
===Repeated===
We use the label ''repeated'' as a cover term for descriptions of multiple instances of the same action, including pluractional descriptions (also sometimes seen as ''pluri-actional'', cf. Bril 2016 <ref name="bril2016">Bril, Isabelle 2016. Tense, aspect and mood in Nêlêmwa (New Caledonia): Encoding events, processes, and states. In: Zlatka Guentchéva (ed.): Aspectuality and Temporality. John Benjamins</ref>). So far, we know that in Daakaka and Dalkalaen pluractionality is often signaled by verb reduplication. In Daakaka, there is also a group of verbs that lexically encode pluractionality. In contrast to labels such as ''iterative'', pluractionality does not imply that multiple actions have to be carried out by the same person. It may also be the case that the same action is carried out by a number of people at the same time. This is illustrated in the following example, which describes a lively scene of children playing on a big log at the beach:
{| class="interlinear" |- ! Tejimre|| nye || ra || -m || yan|| do || '''fya-fyalo''' || ran, || ra || -m || do || bangbang|| ran, || '''taa-taa'''|| ran, || '''mee-meera''' || ran. |- | child || 3P || 3P || -REAL || go || CONT || REDUP-row || on || 3P|| -REAL|| CONT || play || on || REDUP-sit || on || REDUP-jump || on |- | colspan="20" | The children were playing boat on it, they were playing on it, sitting on it and jumping on it. {{Example|Dalkalaen|Competition_380-381}} |}
A special case of pluractional descriptions with multiple actors are reciprocal descriptions:
{| class="interlinear" |- ! yuo-yaa || to || '''yaa-yaa''',|| ye || to || pu || bweak |- | feeling-3D.POSS || NEG|| REDUP-hurt|| 3PC || NEG || blow || swear |- |colspan="20" | They didn't get angry at each other, they didn't swear. {{Example|Daakaka|0003}} |}
The label ''repeated'' also extends to cases where the same action is performed by the same actor, either on the same occasion ('''iterative''' aspect) or on various occasions ('''habitual'''). Non-stative '''generic''' descriptions also fall into this domain. All those cases tend to involve reduplication in Daakaka. Generic descriptions, because of their special modal properties, may be specifically labeled as such with the [[Keywords|keyword]] GENERIC.
Some examples are given below:
* Iterative description:
{| class="interlinear" |- ! gee || mwe || esi || na || sa || sivi || mwe || pwe || '''yaa-yaase''' || nge ||kyu || nge \\ |- | flying.fox|| REAL|| see|| COMP|| CM|| lorikeet|| REAL|| CONT|| REDUP-turn|| 3S|| surround|| 3S |- | colspan="20" | the flying fox saw the lorikeet rotating around himself {{Example|Daakaka|5448}} |}
*Habitual description:
{| class="interlinear" |- ! nate-yaa ||nyoo || ya=m || du || '''deng-deng''' || webung || ke-kevene |- |child-3D.POSS ||3P || 3P=REAL ||stay ||REDUP-cry || day || REDUP-every |- | colspan="20" | their children cried every day {{Example|Daakaka|3033}} |}
*Generic description:
{| class="interlinear" |- ! sini-sye|| nyoo|| mwe || '''tii-tii''' |- | thorn.of-3S.POSS|| 3P || REAL || REDUP-sting |- |colspan="20"| its spikes (can) sting {{Example|Daakaka|1901}} |}
{| class="interlinear" |- ! borvi || mw-i, || mw-i || mesyu || swa || sa, || ya-m || '''an-ane''' |- | str.surgeonfish ||REAL-COP ||REAL-COP ||fish || one ||TOP|| 3P-REAL|| REDUP-eat |- |colspan="20"| The surgeonfish is a fish they eat. {{Example|Daakaka|1906}} |}
===Bounded=== The tag {{Tagname|bounded}} is used to refer to episodic, non-stative event descriptions of the past or future that do not refer to the internal structure of the event.
Some examples are given below:
* ''I went to Paris last year.'' * ''I have been to Paris.'' * A: What are you going to do next? B: ''I'm going to watch a movie.'' * A: What are you going to do next? B: ''I'm going to watch some movies.'' (Here, you can add the [[Keywords|keyword]] PLURAL to make note of the plural object.) * A: What did you do yesterday night? B: ''I took a nice long bath.''
Descriptions of perceptions are labelled as {{Tagname|bounded}} unless they explicitly describe an active process:
* ''She saw a light'' – {{Tagname|bounded}} * ''She was watching the flame'' – {{Tagname|ongoing}} * ''He heard a noise'' – {{Tagname|bounded}} * ''He was listening to the song'' – {{Tagname|ongoing}}
The stimulus of the perception, if given by a predicate, can depend on the semantics of the predicate. Examples: * ''She heard him '''knock''' on the door'' – {{Tagname|bounded}} * ''She heard him '''sing/ singing'''.'' – default: {{Tagname|bounded}} * ''She heard him ['''shout''' her name repeatedly].'' {{Tagname|repeated}}
===Ongoing=== We label event descriptions as {{Tagname|ongoing}} when * they refer specifically to the dynamics of the event's internal development; * they are episodic descriptions of the present moment; * they provide the background for a new development in a narrative;
Examples are given below:
* ''[They were walking along the beach] when they heard someone cry out.'' * ''[He was pulling the tray out of the oven with great care], but then the phone rang and he burned his hand.'' * ''What is she doing right now? [She is smoking.]''
===Change of State== The category "change of state" has been demoted to a keyword. Previous markers of this category will be collapsed with the category {{Tagname|bounded}}.
