{{Tamp|clause=embedded | subtype=conditional | reported=no | time=future|reference| mood=possible| flavor|event=imperfective}}

It appears that in the project languages, the idea of a sequence of events plays a major role. In Saliba, the expression ''kabo'' is used for expressions referring to the future, the generic present and for abilities. But it also appears to mark events that come after other events in a sequence:
{| class="interlinear" |- ! se || kai- || kai|| tamowai|| maudoi|| -na || wa || se || kai- || kai |- | 3PL.SUBJ || DUP- || eat || person || all.of || -3SG.POSS || ANA || 3PL.SUBJ || DUP- || eat |} {| class="interlinear" |- ! ye || lau || boga || -di || wa || ye || sese || '''kabo''' || se || wane |-|| | 3SG.SUBJ || go || stomach || -3PL.OBJ/POSS || ANA || 3SG.SUBJ || swollen || will/then || 3PL.SUBJ || say |- | colspan="20" | they (the village people) were eating, all of them were eating until their bellies were full, and then they said:{{Example|Saliba|BudoiNualele\_01CY\_0470}} |}
Likewise, the two prospective markers in South Efate appear to express a contrast between situations, often in a sequence, which can usually be paraphrased as ''but/and then''.

Mostly, the [[Tagset|tagset]] matches the South Efate data when compared via the Dahl questionnaire: Almost every difference between South Efate constructions corresponds to a different combination of values in the tagset.
There are some exceptions, which are discussed on this page.
===HABIT-related===
In two cases, there is a sequence of sentences referring to a generic scenario, where the first sentence is marked by habitual/ continuous marker ''to'', but the subsequent sentences do not contain this marker:
{| class="interlinear" |- !a= || '''to''' || lek || m̃at || i= || skei |- |1sgRS= || HABIT || look || snake || 3sgRS= || one |- |colspan="20" | (191)(B6) [1'1I tell you what happens to me sometimes when I am walking in the forest.] (191) I SEE a snake. |} {{Tamp|clause=assertion | time=present| mood=actual |event=repeated }}
{| class="interlinear " |- !a= || slat || fat || i= || skei-n |- |1sgRS= || carry || stone || 3sgRS= || one-3sgO |- | colspan="20" | (192) I TAKE a stone and THROW at the snake. |} {{Tamp|clause=assertion | time=present| mood=actual |event=repeated | sequence=yes?}}
{| class="interlinear" !ra= || '''to''' || mes || napu |- | 3d.RS= || HABIT || play || road |- |colspan="20" | (B8) [I'll tell you what I see in the window right now.] (195) A boy and a girl PLAY in the street. |} {{Tamp|clause=assertion | time=present| mood=actual |event=ongoing}}
{| class="interlinear" |- ! malfanen || nanwei || i= || sat || ball || go || i= || nep || ki || -n || tu || nmatu || |- |now || man || 3sgRS= || sat || ball || and || 3sgRS= || throw || PREP || -3sgO || give || female || |- |colspan="20" |(196) (Right now) the boy TAKE a ball and THROW it to the girl. |}
{{Tamp|clause=assertion | time=present| mood=actual |event=ongoing | sequence=yes?}}
The tagset would not show a difference between these sentences, unless one chose to set the value for {{Tagname|sequence}} as ''yes'' in the second clause.
(55) {| class="interlinear" |- ! ore|| i='''po''' || fe || silu || natus|| ne || tefla || ru=nrik-i=n|| kin || ki |- | yes || 3sgRS=PSP:R || read || all || paper || this|| similar || 3p.RS=tell-TR=DST || COMP || PREP |- | colspan="20" | (55) [Q: Your brother DO what his teacher told him to do today?] (Yes) he READ (all of) this book (as he was told) |}
This sentence is tagged in the following way: {{Tamp|clause=assertion | time=past| mood=actual |event=completed | sequence=yes}}
The same values also apply for other simple, completed events in the actual past, but usually those do not involve the prospective. I think the use of the prospective marker here is conditioned by the subsequent sentence (as he was told) to clarify that the command came first and the reading came later. In order to capture this, I included the category {{Tagname|sequence}}.
Something similar seems to be going on with the following two sentences. Again, the difference here can be captured by the category of {{Tagname|sequence}}.
{| class="interlinear" |- !malnen a=mai pak e-sum̃ || nanom || i= || '''po''' || to || mtir || natus || i= || nru |- |as 1sgRS=come to LOC-house || yesterday || 3sgRS= || PSP:R || HABIT || write || paper || 3sgRS= || two |- |colspan="20" | (137) When I COME home (yesterday), he WRITE two letters (=first I came and then he wrote the letters) |}
{| class="interlinear" |- !malnen || a= || mai || pak || e-sum̃ || nanom || '''ki=pe''' || mtir || natus || i= || nru || su |- |as || 1sgRS= || come || to || LOC-house || yesterday || 3sgPS=PF || write || paper || 3sgRS= || two || PF |- | colspan="20"| (138) When I COME home (yesterday), he WRITE two letters (=he finished writing them just before I came) |}
